          "body": "The chapter's structural center is John's question (7:19): *Are You the Expected One, or do we look for someone else?* Jesus' answer (7:22) is a catena of Isaianic phrases — Isaiah 29:18, 35:5-6, and 61:1 — drawn from prophecies of the eschatological renewal. He does not claim the title; He cites the signs. *The blind receive sight, the lame walk, the lepers are cleansed, the deaf hear, the dead are raised up, the poor have the gospel preached to them.* The first two pericopes (Capernaum and Nain) have already supplied the dead being raised and (implicitly) healing-at-a-distance; 7:21 stages a real-time demonstration of the rest. The Coming One is identified by what He DOES, and what He does is the prophesied restoration of Israel — but not the political restoration the establishment expected. *Blessed is he who does not take offense at Me* (7:23) is pastoral, not polemical — Jesus knows the disappointment that comes when the Coming One does not arrive in the predicted form."
